<item>
            <title>[SEC-355] Scheme not supported in AbstractProcessingFilter.defaultTargetUrl</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-355</link>
                <project id="10040" key="SEC">Spring Security</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The JavaDoc for AbstractProcessingFilter states that the defaultTargetUrl supports absolute URLs by starting with a scheme name (the JavaDoc says: The &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;defaultTargetUrl&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt; will be treated as relative to the web-app&apos;s context path, and should include the leading &amp;lt;code&amp;gt;/&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt;. Alternatively, inclusion of a scheme name (eg http:// or &lt;a href=&quot;https://&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://&lt;/a&gt;) as the prefix will denote a fully-qualified URL and this is also supported.)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, the actual code that builds the redirect URL looks like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;            targetUrl = request.getContextPath() + getDefaultTargetUrl();&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;and therefore the full URL just gets appended to the contextPath.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As an aside, it would also be useful if the code for determining the targetUrl was factored out so that it could be overridden easily. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Regards,&lt;br/&gt;
Damien&lt;/p&gt;</description>
